O – Open Closed Principle (OCP)
Definition

Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification.

You should add new functionality without changing existing code.

Bad Example
class AreaCalculator {

    double calculateArea(String shape) {

        if(shape.equals("circle"))
            return 3.14*5*5;

        else if(shape.equals("rectangle"))
            return 10*5;

        return 0;
    }
}
Problem

Suppose Triangle is added.

We need to modify the class again.

This violates OCP.

Good Example
Step 1: Create Interface
interface Shape {
    double area();
}
Step 2: Implement Classes
class Circle implements Shape {

    public double area() {
        return 3.14 * 5 * 5;
    }
}

class Rectangle implements Shape {

    public double area() {
        return 10 * 5;
    }
}
Step 3: Add New Shape
class Triangle implements Shape {

    public double area() {
        return 0.5 * 10 * 8;
    }
}

No existing code is modified.

Real-Life Example

Mobile charger.

A socket remains the same.

Different chargers can be connected without changing the socket.

Benefits

✔ Easy extension

✔ Reduced bugs

✔ More maintainable

✔ Better scalability